## 10. Code Generation Engine

### 10.1 Architecture

```
Code Generation Pipeline:

Project Definition (JSON)
    ↓
AST Generation
    ↓
Code Generation
    ├─→ Next.js (Web)
    ├─→ React Native (Mobile)
    ├─→ API (Backend)
    └─→ Database (SQL)
    ↓
Code Formatting (Prettier)
    ↓
Type Checking (TypeScript)
    ↓
Linting (ESLint)
    ↓
Output Files
```

### 10.2 Project Definition Schema

```typescript
interface ProjectDefinition {
  metadata: {
    id: string;
    name: string;
    description: string;
    version: string;
    createdAt: string;
    updatedAt: string;
  };
  
  settings: {
    uiKit: string;
    modules: InstalledModule[];
    environment: EnvironmentVariables;
    deployment: DeploymentConfig;
  };
  
  screens: Screen[];
  components: ComponentDefinition[];
  functions: AttachedFunction[];
  database: DatabaseSchema;
  api: APIEndpoint[];
  navigation: NavigationConfig;
}
```

### 10.3 Code Generation Process

**Step 1: Parse Project Definition**

```typescript
class CodeGenerator {
  async generate(project: ProjectDefinition): Promise<GeneratedCode> {
    // Validate project
    await this.validate(project);
    
    // Generate AST
    const ast = await this.generateAST(project);
    
    // Generate code from AST
    const code = {
      web: await this.generateWeb(ast),
      mobile: await this.generateMobile(ast),
      api: await this.generateAPI(ast),
      database: await this.generateDatabase(ast)
    };
    
    // Format and validate
    await this.format(code);
    await this.lint(code);
    await this.typeCheck(code);
    
    return code;
  }
}
```

**Step 2: Generate Next.js Code**

```typescript
async generateWeb(ast: ProjectAST): Promise<NextJSProject> {
  return {
    'package.json': this.generatePackageJSON(ast),
    'tsconfig.json': this.generateTSConfig(),
    'tailwind.config.js': this.generateTailwindConfig(ast),
    'next.config.js': this.generateNextConfig(),
    
    'app/': {
      'layout.tsx': this.generateRootLayout(ast),
      'page.tsx': this.generateHomePage(ast),
      ...this.generateScreens(ast.screens)
    },
    
    'components/': {
      'ui/': this.generateUIComponents(ast),
      ...this.generateCustomComponents(ast.components)
    },
    
    'lib/': {
      'supabase.ts': this.generateSupabaseClient(),
      'utils.ts': this.generateUtils()
    },
    
    '.env.local.example': this.generateEnvExample()
  };
}
```

**Step 3: Generate React Native Code**

```typescript
async generateMobile(ast: ProjectAST): Promise<ExpoProject> {
  return {
    'package.json': this.generateMobilePackageJSON(ast),
    'tsconfig.json': this.generateTSConfig(),
    'app.json': this.generateAppJSON(ast),
    'eas.json': this.generateEASConfig(),
    
    'app/': {
      '_layout.tsx': this.generateMobileLayout(ast),
      'index.tsx': this.generateMobileHome(ast),
      ...this.generateMobileScreens(ast.screens)
    },
    
    'components/': {
      ...this.generateMobileComponents(ast.components)
    },
    
    'lib/': {
      'supabase.ts': this.generateMobileSupabaseClient(),
      'utils.ts': this.generateUtils()
    }
  };
}
```

### 10.4 Quality Assurance

**Generated Code Must:**
- Be valid TypeScript
- Pass ESLint with no errors
- Be formatted by Prettier
- Include comprehensive comments
- Have proper error handling
- Use consistent naming conventions
- Follow React best practices
- Be tree-shakeable
- Have no unused imports
- Have no console.log statements (except errors)

